        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down</placeName>
                    <date>Apr. 30<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Huxley</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>It is late at night &amp; I have this minute finished your Address to Geolog. Soc<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>. &amp; I must just thank you for sending it me.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I have read it with uncommon interest. It is a wonderful condensed &amp; original summary on Palæontology, &amp; I should think &amp; hope will do much good.— I hope you are not killing yourself with too much work—</p>
<p>Good night— | yours very sincerely | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.3 &amp; I] ‘&amp;’ <hi rend="italic">over</hi> ‘—’</note>
                </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to Huxley’s anniversary address to the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1841.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Geological Society of London</ref> (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In the absence of the president, Huxley, as one of the secretaries of the Geological Society, delivered the anniversary address on 21 February 1862 (T. H. Huxley 1862d). The president, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2392.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Leonard Horner</ref>, was in Italy with his convalescent wife.</note>
        </div>        
            
